(20, 1, '2021-06-18 13:56:14', '2021-06-18 13:56:14', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As NATO and G7 leaders met to discuss a tougher line on China this week, Taiwan – swiftly emerging as the most serious likely flashpoint – was entering a new phase of its perfect storm with the mainland.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Taiwan’s defence minister said on Tuesday that 26 Chinese warplanes entered the Air Defence Identification Zone claimed by Taiwan, one more than the previous largest incursion in April. The aircraft – including jet interceptors, maritime patrol aircraft and nuclear-capable bombers – flew around the south of Taiwan and near a much smaller disputed island.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Beijing’s military rhetoric and actions towards Taiwan – which China argues is a rogue province that must be reintegrated with the mainland – have ramped up sharply this year, particularly air and maritime incursions. This has prompted a similar uptick in supportive moves from the United States, including sending destroyers through waters between Taiwan and China.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Tensions are clearly rising – from the USS Ronald Reagan carrier battle group just arriving in the South China Sea to Chinese dredgers encroaching into Taiwanese waters. Both Beijing and Washington are looking to unambiguously demonstrate their seriousness in planning for any future conflict, neither really knowing how genuine or committed the other truly is.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>It is a dynamic already worrying US and Western tech manufacturers – Taiwan is one of the world’s largest producers, and a conflict there could devastate an industry already struggling with capacity issues.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For decades, the United States has been deliberately ambiguous and vague in its expressions of support for Taiwan, an approach first formally adopted with the 1979 Taiwan Relations Act. The last year of the Trump administration and first of Biden, however, have seen a much more assertive line – with pressure from Congress to go much further.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'For Taiwan, China, vaccines and geopolitics spark perfect storm', 'As NATO and G7 leaders met to discuss a tougher line on China this week, Taiwan – swiftly emerging as the most serious likely flashpoint – was entering a new phase of its perfect storm with the mainland.', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '18-revision-v1', '', '', '2021-06-18 13:56:14', '2021-06-18 13:56:14', '', 18, 'http://localhost/WordPress/supershop/?p=20', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(22, 1, '2021-06-18 14:01:37', '2021-06-18 14:01:37', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Carmakers that saw nearly a decade of Indian sales growth wiped out in 2020 are expecting a bounce back in demand this year. But it is likely to be led by small, affordable cars - a sector dominated by homegrown leader Maruti Suzuki and rival Hyundai - rather than the premium models churned out by most foreign manufacturers, industry executives and analysts say.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>With their Indian factories running well below capacity and sales far behind original hopes, firms like Ford, Honda, Nissan, Skoda and Volkswagen face difficult decisions about future investments.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\"It is a survival issue,\" said one senior executive with a Western automaker who declined to be named.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\"Choosing to remain in India depends on the cost benefit analysis of other international markets,\" the executive added, forecasting that, if the outlook remains grim, the number of automakers in the country could fall.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>India has already seen General Motors and Harley-Davidson shut up shop last year.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Anurag Mehrotra, managing director at Ford India, told Reuters the car market had not grown as projected and COVID had made matters worse, hurting domestic sales and exports.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\"The uncertainty in the long-term growth prospects of the auto industry and economy have resulted in serious challenges, including capacity utilisation,\" Mehrotra said.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>He said the pandemic demanded “agile solutions and tough decisions,” but did not give details of Ford’s plans. The US automaker has said previously it is working on a new plan for India.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Volkswagen, which revised its India strategy in 2018 putting its sister company Skoda in charge, reiterated its plan to invest $1.2 billion to corner 5% of the market by 2025 with new launches, starting with two SUVs this year.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The ambition is to continue building and reinforcing the group\'s position in the Indian market, a spokesperson for the local unit, Skoda Auto Volkswagen India, said.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Honda and Nissan did not respond to emails seeking comment.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'COVID deals new blow to foreign carmakers’ Indian dream', 'Carmakers that saw nearly a decade of Indian sales growth wiped out in 2020 are expecting a bounce back in demand this year. But it is likely to be led by small, ', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'covid-deals-new-blow-to-foreign-carmakers-indian-dream', '', '', '2021-06-18 14:03:09', '2021-06-18 14:03:09', '', 0, 'http://localhost/WordPress/supershop/?p=22', 0, 'post', '', 0),
